hands_on_practices.problem:
A particle of mass $m$ is confined to a one-dimensional infinite potential well of length $L$, extending from $x=0$ to $x=L$. At time $t=0$, the particle's state is not an energy eigenstate but is described by the normalized wavefunction:
$$
\Psi(x, 0) =
\begin{cases}
\sqrt{\frac{12}{L^3}} x & \text{for } 0 \leq x \leq \frac{L}{2} \\
\sqrt{\frac{12}{L^3}} (L-x) & \text{for } \frac{L}{2} < x \leq L \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$
If a measurement of the particle's total energy is performed at a time $t>0$, what is the probability of obtaining the energy value corresponding to the first excited state ($n=2$)? Express your answer as an exact analytic expression.
